the places where the cures are ... wait now ... [_Reads._] "Compound medicines are usually taken 

inwardly, or outwardly applied. Inwardly taken they should be either liquid or solid; outwardly they 

should be fomentations or sponges wet in some decoctions."  THOMAS. He had a right to have 

written it out himself upon a paper. Where is the use of all that?  ANDREW. I think I moved the 

mark maybe ... here now is the part he was reading to me himself ... "the remedies for diseases 

belonging to the skins next the brain: headache, vertigo, cramp, convulsions, palsy, incubus, 

apoplexy, falling sickness."  THOMAS. It is what I bid you to tell him--that it was the falling 

